  "text": "Consumer offset management in Kafka spans two main modules: the server-side group-coordinator and the client-side consumer internals.\n\n**OffsetAndMetadata storage**: The server-side record type is `group-coordinator/.../OffsetAndMetadata.java`, with serialization handled by `GroupCoordinatorRecordHelpers` (builds OffsetCommit records) and `GroupCoordinatorRecordSerde` (serializes/deserializes them for the `__consumer_offsets` topic, defined in `Topic.java`). The client-side DTO is `clients/.../consumer/OffsetAndMetadata.java`.\n\n**GroupCoordinator offset commit handler**: The `GroupCoordinator` interface defines `commitOffsets`/`fetchOffsets`. `GroupCoordinatorService` is the top-level implementation that delegates to `GroupCoordinatorShard`, which in turn delegates to `OffsetMetadataManager.commitOffset()`. `GroupCoordinatorConfig` holds offset retention settings.\n\n**OffsetFetch request processing**: Client-side, `OffsetsRequestManager` and `CommitRequestManager` build `OffsetFetchRequest`/`OffsetCommitRequest` objects. Server-side, `GroupCoordinatorService.fetchOffsets()` -> `GroupCoordinatorShard` -> `OffsetMetadataManager.fetchOffsets()` processes the fetch. `OffsetFetcher` and `OffsetFetcherUtils` handle client-side response processing. `ConsumerCoordinator` handles the legacy consumer path.\n\n**Offset expiry/compaction**: `OffsetMetadataManager.cleanupExpiredOffsets()` drives expiry. It uses the `Group.offsetExpirationCondition()` interface method, implemented per group type (`ClassicGroup`, `ConsumerGroup`, `ShareGroup`, `StreamsGroup`). `OffsetExpirationCondition` and `OffsetExpirationConditionImpl` encapsulate the expiry logic. `GroupMetadataManager` manages group lifecycle that interacts with offset cleanup.",
